I've never been to Turkey, but this restaurant definitely makes me want to visit now. My fiancée and I had recently dined here for dinner and had one of the best experiences the year. Our great server helped guide us through the menu and made some personal recommendations from the cocktails to the dessert... and everything was fantastic.  For drinks, we started off with "The Spice Trade" (a Mediterranean twist on the Old Fashioned) and the "Mediterranean Mule" (pretty self-explanatory), both of which were perfect. It was then that we knew that we were in for a treat. We went on to some cold and hot mezze - a trio of Hummus Sumac, Muhammara (Roasted red pepper dip), and Mutabbal (Smoked eggplant) along with Halloumi skewers - everything perfectly sized for sharing between 2-4 of your closest friends. We then tried the Sucuklu Pide, which is a boat-shaped flat bread made with Spiced Turkish sausage and mozzarella, as well as Truffled Scallops and Roasted Short Ribs. The short ribs were fall-off-the-bone tender and packed with flavor, definitely one of my favorite dishes on the night. We finished with traditional Turkish desserts - Baklava and Kunefe (Shredded wheat pastry, unsalted cheese, pistachio, kaymak). Both desserts were beautifully prepared, well-balanced, and had just enough sweetness.  Overall, a stellar experience with top-notch service and next-level food. With the ambiance, hospitality, and extensive menu, Ankara is a great choice for any occasion from a casual night with friends or date night with that special someone. Pro tip: Leave room for dessert. As someone who's not big on desserts in general, just trust me.

She was amazing, beyond knowledgeable about both food and drinks, super professional at first but when we made it clear we were chill and enjoyed chatting, she took the time to stay and have a conversation with us which made our experience even better...it's the experience that makes people go back to a restaurant...not to be confused with service...a robot could give you great service but only a truly talented server can give you an experience that you'll remember and write about! The bottomless lasted I think 2 hours with dessert and coffee as part of the package and was only $39! Unbelievable deal...you could barely get beer and pizza for that price never mind exquisite food, drinks and service in an upscale establishment. We went to Ankara for their bottomless brunch during restaurant week at around 1:45pm.  The good: the food was okay and the small plates generally came out quickly. I especially liked their bread & apricot jam, hummus, carrot hummus, mücver, chocolate cake, baklava, and tea.  The bad: while their menu offers a good variety of items, please beware that they may not have every item on the menu, especially toward the end of the brunch period. This is normally not an issue I care too much about because I understand that food supplies are finite, but I was very put off when servers did not bother to ask if we wanted substitute items when notifying us that they were out of the items we had chosen. On two separate occasions severs told us they were out of a menu item and then they quickly walked away to service others. The most off-putting experience occurred after we ordered Turkish coffee and dessert. You normally want to have coffee and dessert together, ya? I would argue that's a perfectly normal expectation. Well, they brought out the dessert but no Turkish coffee and supplied no information about when it would come. After waiting for nearly 10 minutes, we asked a server if the Turkish coffee was on the way and he said the machine was malfunctioning and that he would try to get it to work. After a couple of minutes, the Turkish coffee came out but another perfectly normal expectation was not met - it was (nearly) ice cold! I've been to Istanbul thrice and have never heard of such a thing! If their quality control falls short when it comes to Turkish coffee preparation, something that a Turkish restaurant should do perfectly, I have to question their entire food production process. Sadly, while I'm a fan of Turkish cuisine, I cannot recommend this eatery. Go somewhere else for Turkish fare!
